The '''International Islamic News Agency (IINA)''', a specialized organ of the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] (OIC), is a news agency publishing in [[Arabic]], [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]] and focusing on news about the Islamic world and Islamic affairs. Its headquarters is in [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]].
The agency was established in 1972,<ref>{{cite journal|title=A Comparative Study on the Pan-Arab Media Strategies: The Cases of Egypt and Saudi Arabia|date=February 2012|volume=5|issue=1&2|url=http://www.asafas.kyoto-u.ac.jp/kias/pdf/kb5_1and2/07chiba.pdf|accessdate=13 February 2014|author=Chiba Yushi}}</ref> under a resolution of the Third Islamic Conference of Foreign Ministers. It is financed by OIC member states, especially [[Saudi Arabia]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Qatar]], [[Pakistan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Indonesia]], [[Egypt]], [[Libya]], [[Morocco]], and [[Tunisia]]. [[Abdulaziz bin Mohieddin Khoja]] is chairman of the International Islamic News Agency (IINA) Executive Council.<ref name=bna1012>{{cite news|title=IAAs BNA Elected as IINA Executive Council Member|url=http://www.iaa.bh/news-details.aspx?id=70|accessdate=28 August 2012|work=Bahrain News Agency|date=10 December 2011}}</ref>
