== Notes on numbering of popes ==

A number of anomalies in the list given above need further explanation:

* [[Antipope Felix II|Felix II]] (356–357), [[Boniface VII]] (974, 984–985), [[Antipope John XVI|John&nbsp;XVI]] (997–998), [[Antipope Benedict X|Benedict&nbsp;X]] (1058–1059) and [[Antipope Alexander V|Alexander&nbsp;V]] (1409–1410) are not listed because they are all considered [[antipope]]s.<ref name="ceanti">{{CathEncy|author=Paschal Robinson|wstitle=Antipope}}</ref>
* The numbering of popes named Felix has been amended to omit antipope [[Antipope Felix II|Felix&nbsp;II]]; however, most lists still call the last two Felixes: [[Pope Felix III|Felix&nbsp;III]] and [[Pope Felix IV|Felix&nbsp;IV]]. Additionally, there was an antipope [[antipope Felix V|Felix&nbsp;V]].<ref name="ceanti" />
* There has never been a pope [[Pope John XX|John&nbsp;XX]] as a result of [[Pope John (numbering)|confusion of the numbering system]] in the 11th century.<ref name="cechron">{{CathEncy|author=Paschal Robinson|wstitle=Chronological Lists of Popes}}</ref>
* [[Pope-elect Stephen]], who died before being consecrated, has not been on the Vatican's official list of popes since 1961, but appears on lists dating from before 1960.<ref name="cechron" /> The numbering of following popes called ''Stephen'' are nowadays given as [[Pope Stephen II]] (752–757) to [[Pope Stephen IX]] (1057–1058), rather than Stephen&nbsp;III to Stephen&nbsp;X.
* When Simon de Brion became pope in 1281, he chose to be called ''Martin''. At that time, [[Pope Marinus I|Marinus&nbsp;I]] and [[Pope Marinus II|Marinus&nbsp;II]] were mistakenly considered to be Martin II and Martin III respectively, and so, erroneously, Simon de Brion became [[Pope Martin IV]].<ref name="cemartin">{{CathEncy|author=Paschal Robinson|wstitle=Pope Martin IV}}</ref>
* [[Pope Donus II]], said to have reigned about 974, never existed. The belief resulted from the confusion of the title ''dominus'' (lord) with a proper name.
* [[Pope Joan]] also never existed; however, legends about her may have originated from stories about the [[Saeculum obscurum|pornocracy]].<ref name="ceJoan">{{CathEncy|author=Paschal Robinson|wstitle=Popess Joan}}</ref>
*The status of [[Antipope John XXIII]] was uncertain for hundreds of years, and was finally settled in 1958 when Angelo Giuseppe Roncalli announced his own name as John&nbsp;XXIII. Baldassare Cossa, who was Antipope John&nbsp;XXIII, served as a Cardinal of the reunited church before his death in 1419 and his remains are found in the [[Florence Baptistery]].
* Those who believe in [[Sedevacantism]] say that there have been no legitimate popes since Pius XII or John XXIII. This is because they consider all popes since the [[Second Vatican Council]] to be [[heretic]]s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=yUqp1_31B-MC&pg=PA257&dq=Sedevacantism#v=onepage&q=Sedevacantism&f=false Weaver, MJ., and Appleby, RS., ''Being Right: Conservative Catholics in America'', Indiana University Press, 1 Jan 1995, p. 257.]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gxEONS0FFlsC&pg=PA566&dq=Sedevacantism#v=onepage&q=Sedevacantism&f=false Flinn, FK., ''Encyclopedia of Catholicism'', 2007, p. 566.]</ref>

