'''Lithomancy''' is a form of [[divination]] by which the future is told using stones or the reflected light from said stones. The practice is most popular in the [[British Isles]].<ref name="book1">{{Cite book  | last = Cheung  | first = Theresa  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = The Element Encyclopedia of the Psychic World  | publisher = Harper Element  | series =   | volume =   | edition =   | year = 2006  | location =   | pages = 401  | url =   | doi =   | id =   | isbn =  978-0-00-721148-7  | mr =   | zbl =   | jfm = }}</ref>

==History==

The earliest verified account of lithomancy comes from [[Photius]], the patriarch of [[Constantinople]], who describes a physician named Eusebius using a stone called a [[wikt:baetulus|baetulum]] to perform the ritual.<ref name="book1"/><ref>{{cite book|title=An Encyclopaedia of Occultism|last=Spence|first= Lewis|publisher=Dover Publications|page=252|year=2003|ISBN=978-0-486-42613-6}}</ref> However, some writers also claim that [[Helenus]] predicted the destruction of [[Troy]] using the ritual.<ref>{{Cite book  | last = Elworthy  | first = Frederick Thomas   | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Evil Eye the Origins and Practices of Superstition  | publisher = Kessinger Publishing  | series =   | volume =   | edition =   | year = 2003  | location =   | pages = 444–445  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zQRFFQuhLnYC&pg=PA444&dq=%22lithomancy%22&hl=en&ei=eQITTozdB86ChQfEm_H1DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAzge#v=onepage&q=%22lithomancy%22&f=false  | doi =   | id =   | isbn = 978-0-7661-3242-9  | mr =   | zbl =   | jfm = }}</ref>

==Practice==

In modern lithomancy{{clarify|date=August 2015}}, 13 stones are tossed onto a board and a prediction made based on the pattern in which they fall. The stones are representative of various concepts: fortune, magic, love, news, home life and the astrological planets of Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, the sun, and the moon.<ref>{{cite book|title=Witchcraft Today: An Encyclopedia of Wiccan and Neopagan Traditions|last=Lewis|first=James R.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|ISBN=978-1-57607-134-2|year=1999|page=177}}</ref>

