'''Madame de Thèbes''' (1845 &ndash; 1916), [[pseudonym]] of '''Anne Victorine Savigny''' was a [[French people|French]] [[clairvoyant]] and [[palm reader]]. She plied her trade from her living room at No. 29 [[Avenue de Wagram]] in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=puXmVBQSCjAC&pg=PA76 |title=Pierre Mac Orlan: His Life, His Time |accessdate=27 December 2013|isbn=9782600036931 |last1=Baritaud |first1=Bernard |year=1992 }}</ref> Every Christmas, she published her [[prophecy|prophecies]] in an ''Almanac'', which enjoyed wide circulation. She was said to have predicted:<ref name="nyt">{{cite news | title = Mme. de Thebes's War Prophecies | newspaper = The New York Times | volume =| issue =| date = 21 March 1915 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/03/21/119029439.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = April 8, 2010}}</ref>
* The [[Boer War]];
* The [[Russo-Japanese War]];
* Triggers of [[World War I]];
* The violent death of [[General Boulanger]];
* The tragic death of [[Catulle Mendès]];
* The death of [[William Thomas Stead]];
* The case of [[Henriette Caillaux|Caillaux]].

She published the book ''The Enigma of the Dream: Explanation of Dreams'' in 1908.<ref>{{cite book | author= Madame de Thèbes | title =L'énigme du Rêve: Explication des Songes   |trans-title=The Enigma of the Dream: Explanation of Dreams |publisher = Librairie Felix Juven | location = Paris | year = 1908 |url= http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5601288s.r=Th%C3%A8bes.langFR | language = FR |accessdate = 21 June 2011}}</ref>

